sidered just an enhancement to add. <br>
<br>
(1) is easy to figure out: If I type /camp desktop and it doesn't camp me to the desktop despite the help screens saying it should, it's a (1). <br>
<br>
(2) is slightly harder but still easy: if &quot;Electric Shock of Karana&quot; is a level 65 spell that does 10hp of damage, then even though it never SAID it should do more, since it's level 65 it's clearly unintended, so it's a (2). <br>
<br>
(3) is the toughy, so I usually make sure I have a good solid case particular to the bug before submitting one of these: if wizards had a fire, ice and magic nuke for every fifth level from 30 to 65 EXCEPT that there was no ice nuke for 55, I'd argue that there is no special reason why 55 is less special than the other levels and therefore really ought to have an ice nuke, so a (3).<br>
<br>
This is how I'd define a bug in EQ. I can then define an exploit to be a bug that, overall, benefits users who encounter it.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tigertailz>tigertailz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Evoker</span><br>  Posts: 444<br> <font color=#ffffff>(3/29/03 11:34:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25564.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: .</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I think that an exploit is any action that is used for the benifit of the doer that was not intended as a feature and gives the doer an unfair advantage.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
