<br>
As a noun, an <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>exploit</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is a situation that exists such that a player can take advantage of a bug or unintended design consequence to achieve an unfair advantage over other players, especially in terms of items, platinum, experience, or spawn competition.  Also any situation that allows harassment of other players or the ability to make gains with <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>zero</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> risk would be an exploit.  More generally, the use of bugs and unintended features to generally break the foundations of the game and make it generally less fun.<br>
<br>
I think as a working definition, it's important to recognize the varying levels of damage caused by a situation.  The ability to duplicate items, for example, would ruin the game's economy, which would ruin the game's fun for a lot of people.  Such an exploit would require urgent attention from developers and players exploiting that exploit(/sigh) would suffer serious consequences.  Similarly, the ability to crash a zone both gives advantages in terms of spawn competition and ruins the play experience of others.  This would be another major exploit.  The horse/models exploit would be an example of a minor exploit.  A player that could duck and move a sow speed didn't have really large measureable advantages over a player with models on.  However some advantages were there, med benefits without associated drawbacks was not intended, thus it would properly be defined as an &quot;exploit&quot; although not one that should result in bannings or urgent developer attention.<br>
<br>
